a-size-base: Smaller and softer treats for smaller/older dogs
a-size-base 2: Reviewed in the United States on September 25, 2021
a-size-base 3: We got these because our 15 year old chihuahua is very healthy for her age, but not able to eat anything hard because of some dental issues.We figured if she can get these down, they help her nutritionally, and make her happy, that would be a huge win.Regarding how she took to them...At first, she didn't eat these treats at all, but she is very fussy about food in general.Leaving a few near her favorite sleeping spot, she eventually decided she could deign to eat them as a snack.If you have a dog who is very into treats, I suspect they will gobble these up without hesitation.The treats themselves are: covered with some sort of yellow powder; they are quite small; their texture is soft, but not squishy, and though they have a scent, it is neither intense, nor unpleasant.As shown on the product page, the recommended serving is 8 to 10 treats for dogs 5 lbs and up.Whet they arrived, the treats had a best by date just over six months away, so they're not a treat you can keep on a back shelf forever.One thing I did not like is that they do not specify where these are produced.The company that sells them is based in Texas, but they do not state whether they are manufactured there, which leaves me wondering where they actually come from.Our picky lady does not eat these until she feels like it, but can manage them, even with some dental issues, so I think they are a good choice for senior dogs.She also has experienced no negative side effects from taking them, so that is obviously a big plus in and of itself.I would say if you are looking for a treat for an older dog that is small and easy for them to get down, this would be a good one to try.
